assumptions:
  - "HttpChecker.check already returns a CheckOutcome with body populated and 1 MiB-truncated (established in Slice 1); ContentMatchChecker can consume it as-is without needing HttpChecker changes"
  - "The HTTP follow_redirects and expected_status_codes options are deferred to Slice 8; content-match inherits whatever default HttpChecker uses for the current slice (no redirect following, default 200-399 status classification)"
  - "String#include? handles nil-body safely via body.to_s, returning false when body is nil"

specifications:
  - "ContentMatchChecker.check(url:, pattern:) takes two primitive args; the dispatcher extracts url and pattern from the Site record"
  - "ContentMatchChecker passes an HTTP failure (error_message present) through unchanged — content-match inherits transport-level failures"
  - "ContentMatchChecker sets metadata[:matched] to an explicit true or false; absence is never the signal"
  - "ContentMatchChecker does NOT set error_message on a match miss — classification stays in the job via metadata[:matched]"
  - "ContentMatchChecker preserves pattern in metadata[:pattern] for future debugging and for the future 3-state metadata shape in Slice 10"
  - "PerformCheckJob#derive_status returns :down when result.metadata[:matched] == false, ordered after the error_message check and before the HTTP 200-399 classification"
  - "The metadata[:matched] check uses explicit == false so HTTP and other check types with an empty metadata hash are unaffected"
  - "Site validates content_match_pattern presence and length (<= CONTENT_MATCH_PATTERN_MAX = 500) only when check_type is :content_match"
  - "Site#clear_irrelevant_config nulls content_match_pattern on any non-:content_match save"
  - "SiteFormComponent labels :content_match as 'HTTP content match' in the check_type select"
  - "SiteForm::ContentMatchFieldsComponent renders the 1 MiB truncation helper text so the accepted-trade-off is visible to operators in the UI"
  - "Content-match sites still render the url field (they use HTTP under the hood, the url is required)"

deviations_from_plan: >
  Plan's Slice 6 text described extending HttpChecker::Result with a body
  field "in this slice" — but body was already added in Slice 1 when the
  CheckOutcome value object was established. Slice 6's ContentMatchChecker
  uses body as-is, no HttpChecker changes needed. Not a drift concern,
  just a plan-text artifact from an earlier draft.

  Plan's Slice 6 text also mentioned ContentMatchChecker accepting
  follow_redirects and expected_status_codes kwargs that forward to
  HttpChecker. Those options don't exist until Slice 8 — deferred to
  Slice 8's retrofit.

trade_offs: >
  metadata[:matched] as the contract rather than setting error_message
  on a miss. Cost: the job has a third branch in derive_status that
  knows about the key name. Benefit: per decision 3, classification
  lives in the job, and metadata is the correct shape for "raw signals
  the checker produces". The alternative (error_message populated on
  miss) would move classification into the checker and violate the rule.
  Slice 10 will extend this pattern when SSL adds metadata[:classification]
  for 3-state.

  String#include? against the full 1 MiB body on every check. Cost:
  O(n) memory scan per check, worst case 1 MiB. Benefit: the simplest
  possible match, no regex compilation cost, no ReDoS risk. The 60s
  cadence makes the CPU cost trivial. If operators need regex matching
  later it's a separate follow-up.

  Truncation false-negative (pattern beyond 1 MiB never matches) is
  surfaced in the form helper text rather than hidden. Operators see
  the limit before they configure the check.

interfaces:
  consumed:
    - "HttpChecker.check(url) -> CheckOutcome"
    - "CheckOutcome.new(status_code:, response_time_ms:, error_message:, checked_at:, body:, metadata:) -> CheckOutcome"
    - "Site#check_type -> String"
    - "Site#content_match_pattern -> String | nil"
    - "Site#url -> String"
  published:
    - "ContentMatchChecker.check(url:, pattern:) -> CheckOutcome"
    - "CheckDispatcher.call(site) -> CheckOutcome | raises CheckDispatcher::UnknownCheckType"
    - "Site#content_match? -> Boolean"
    - "Site#content_match_pattern= (string writer)"
    - "Site::CONTENT_MATCH_PATTERN_MAX -> 500"
    - "SiteForm::ContentMatchFieldsComponent.new(form:, site:) -> component"

self_review:
  tests: >
    Added spec/services/content_match_checker_spec.rb with 6 cases: matching
    body → matched true, non-matching body → matched false with no error_message,
    transport failure passes through, empty body → matched false, nil body →
    matched false (nil-safe via to_s), pattern stored in metadata. Extended
    check_dispatcher_spec.rb with a :content_match dispatch case asserting the
    url+pattern translation from the Site record. Added two job spec cases:
    metadata[:matched] = false → site goes down, metadata[:matched] = true →
    site goes up. Extended site_spec.rb with content_match_pattern validation
    (presence, length), and added a clear_irrelevant_config case for flipping
    content_match back to http. Extended site_form_component_spec.rb with a
    :content_match rendering context (pattern input, helper text, url still
    present). Added new_content_match_site preview variant.
  consistency: >
    ContentMatchChecker follows the Slice 4/5 pattern of class-method entrypoint,
    single same-named instance method, private helpers — except it has no private
    helpers beyond what's needed because the happy path is a single expression.
    The metadata[:matched] contract mirrors the pattern Slice 10 will use for
    SSL metadata[:classification]. The SiteForm::ContentMatchFieldsComponent
    class body is identical to the other SiteForm:: leaf components (same
    initialize, attr_reader, field_error helper) — noted in Slice 5 as a
    base-class refactor candidate, deferred to a follow-up issue.
  metz: >
    Measured. content_match_checker.rb is 35 lines, 2 public methods (self.check
    1 body line, check 10 body lines because of the branching on HTTP failure
    then the metadata construction). The 10-line check method is over Metz's
    5-line rule but kept as one method — splitting it into "inherit_failure"
    and "build_match_outcome" helpers would obscure the single happy-path
    expression. site.rb is now 73 lines with a fifth scrub line in
    clear_irrelevant_config. check_dispatcher.rb 34 lines. site_form_component.html.erb
    stayed roughly level — ContentMatchFieldsComponent is rendered through
    the dispatcher so the shell didn't grow.
  duplication: >
    Five SiteForm:: leaf components now share the same 9-line class body
    (initialize + attr_reader + field_error helper). Extraction to a
    SiteForm::FieldsComponent base class is justified by repetition and
    filed as a follow-up — a base class with one optional override method
    for the field_error helper would cut ~40 lines of boilerplate across
    the five leaves. Not done in this slice to avoid mid-epic refactor.
  mocking: >
    content_match_checker_spec mocks HttpChecker.check — owned internal
    code. No external network touched. CheckOutcome fixtures are
    constructed directly (owned value object).
  error_paths: >
    HTTP failure inheritance is the primary error path. ContentMatchChecker
    returns the HTTP outcome unchanged when error_message.present? — no
    wrapping, no new error types. The match miss case is not an error
    (error_message stays nil); the job derives :down from metadata.
  security: >
    The SsrfGuard protection is inherited through HttpChecker — ContentMatchChecker
    never touches Faraday or sockets directly. The 500-character pattern
    limit prevents trivially large input from bloating check configs; the
    1 MiB body truncation prevents memory exhaustion from a malicious server
    returning enormous bodies. No regex compilation, no ReDoS risk.
  performance: >
    One extra String#include? call per HTTP content-match check. Scales
    with body length (O(n * m) worst case where n is body bytes and m is
    pattern length), bounded by 1 MiB body and 500-char pattern. A single
    check runs in milliseconds; a 60s cadence per site is nowhere near
    saturating.
  api: >
    Additive. ContentMatchChecker is new. Site#content_match?,
    Site#content_match_pattern, Site::CONTENT_MATCH_PATTERN_MAX are new.
    CheckDispatcher gains a fifth branch. PerformCheckJob#derive_status
    gains one new line. Existing :http/:ssl/:tcp/:dns sites are unaffected
    because their metadata never has a [:matched] key so the == false
    check is always false for them.
  dead_code: >
    None. ContentMatchChecker consumes HttpChecker.check, pattern lives on
    the Site, the form component is rendered via the dispatcher.

